{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01QgxJ75NgmsDqPH812f338H","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1: Speech-to-text output preserves speaker labels so that the summary can attribute statements to specific attendees.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about whether the speech-to-text API actually returns speaker labels. Could fail at the API boundary.\n- REAL-INFRA: Depends on real speech-to-text API behavior - whether it actually returns speaker diarization labels. An in-process fake wouldn't catch if the real API doesn't return speaker labels as expected.\n- LLM-DEP: The speech-to-text part is not an LLM per se, but it IS an AI/ML model (speaker diarization is ML). \n\nThe core issue is whether the real STT API actually returns speaker labels—mocking it would just return whatever we programmed in, hiding the real API's actual behavior. The behavior itself is about the end-to-end capability of attributing statements to attendees, which means I need to test whether the real API provides diarization, not just whether our code can parse labels if they exist.\n\nSince speaker diarization is an ML task whose quality depends on the actual model, this needs to be tested at the Agentic level.\n\nFor the second behavior about action items, the failure mode is whether the LLM correctly identifies and extracts tasks assigned to each attendee.\n\nThe third behavior around decisions versus narrative is also LLM-dependent—it's about the model's ability to properly categorize and structure content.\n\nFor the fourth behavior with longer audio files, I need to consider whether the segmentation and merging logic works correctly across multiple processing stages. The full pipeline with real audio upload, STT, LLM summarization, and structured output delivery across multiple sequential steps is definitely Workflow level. Now I'm assigning probability weights to each behavior based on what testing level would actually catch the real issues — Unit testing won't expose the actual STT speaker diarization behavior, Integration with mocks hides real service behavior, System testing with real HTTP calls gets closer but the ML component is still a black box, and Agentic testing is where I'd catch whether the full orchestration works end-to-end. Now I'm looking at the remaining behaviors and their weightings. Behavior 5 is almost entirely workflow-dependent since it's testing the full end-to-end pipeline. For behavior 1, I need to clarify whether the speaker diarization test is really about the code's ability to pass labels through the system versus whether the underlying ML model actually detects speakers in real audio—those are fundamentally different failure modes that would require different test approaches.\n\nThe core issue with behavior 4 is that \"merging results into a coherent summary\" involves multiple sequential agentic steps: several STT calls across segments plus an LLM call to combine them. The coherence of the final output depends on real model behavior, not just orchestration logic, so this should weight toward workflow-level testing.\n\nNow I'm checking whether my test level assignments stay consistent across all behaviors. For behaviors 1-3, agentic-level tests make sense since each involves a single real model call. Behaviors 4-5 both require the full segmented pipeline with multiple model invocations, so they both need workflow-level testing. This alignment confirms my assessment is coherent.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9554,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9554},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4f25edd2-cd56-49c8-ba5b-0f6c36e01bb8","uuid":"cd5170a4-37be-47df-8f81-8ae3d4d85099"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01QgxJ75NgmsDqPH812f338H","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_0173RjameTDajbTMcdLspkyX","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Speech-to-text output preserves speaker labels so the summary can attribute statements to specific attendees.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure could exist at the code level (not threading speaker labels through) OR at the STT API level (not returning diarization). REAL-INFRA: Real HTTP to the STT API is needed. MOCK-HIDE: A stub STT response hard-codes whatever speaker labels the test author invents — it cannot reveal whether the real STT API returns diarization data at all, whether it handles overlapping speakers, or whether its label format matches what the downstream parser expects. LLM-DEP: Speaker diarization is an ML/AI task; the real model's ability to identify and consistently label speakers across a real audio stream is non-deterministic and cannot be validated by a stub. REJECTION-GATE: Nothing in the behavior description limits the test to 'does the parser correctly handle a label field that is already present' — the behavior explicitly couples STT output quality to summary attribution, so we cannot demote below Agentic.","test_description":"Submit a real audio recording with at least two identifiable speakers to the live STT API. Assert that the response payload contains speaker labels (e.g., 'Speaker 1', 'Speaker 2') and that each transcript segment is tagged with a speaker identifier. Then verify that downstream parsing retains those labels in the structure passed to the LLM prompt.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.14,"Agentic":0.62,"Workflow":0.14}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The structured summary contains at least one action item for every attendee who was assigned a task during the meeting.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-HIDE: A stub LLM returns whatever action items the test author pre-programs. It cannot reveal whether a real model fails to extract an assignment buried in indirect phrasing ('let's have Sarah handle that'), misattributes it, or omits one of several assigned attendees. LLM-DEP: Correctness depends entirely on the LLM's ability to identify task assignments and link them to specific attendees — a classification/extraction judgment made by the real model. Deterministic-assertion trap: the assertion 'at least one action item per assigned attendee' is perfectly deterministic, but the fixture that validates it replaces the LLM's actual judgment with a constant, making any extraction failure invisible. REJECTION-GATE: No part of the behavior constrains the test to infrastructure (routing, retries, payload shape) independent of model output — the whole behavior is about what the model produces.","test_description":"Feed a real curated transcript (with named attendees and explicit task assignments) to the live LLM summarization step. Assert that the returned 'action_items' list contains at least one entry per attendee who was explicitly assigned a task, with the correct attendee name attached. Run against multiple transcript samples covering direct ('Bob will do X') and indirect ('let's have Carol handle Y') phrasing.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.19}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Key decisions mentioned in the transcript appear in the 'decisions' section of the summary, not buried in the narrative.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: The failure is the LLM misclassifying a decision as narrative — a content-routing judgment that only the real model makes. A stub always returns the correct bucket because the test author writes what goes where, making every stub test a tautology. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the LLM replaces its classification logic with a constant; any prompt-engineering failure or model regression that causes decisions to leak into the narrative section is completely invisible. REJECTION-GATE: The behavior is not about whether the code builds a 'decisions' key in the JSON (that is a schema test, Unit/Integration) — it is about whether the real LLM routes content into the right section. Nothing in the description limits it to schema shape alone.","test_description":"Send a known transcript containing clearly stated decisions (e.g., 'We decided to launch in Q3') and deliberative narrative to the live LLM. Assert that every pre-identified decision phrase appears in the 'decisions' list and that none appear exclusively in a 'summary' or 'narrative' field. Use multiple transcripts with decisions stated at varying explicitness levels.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.14}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the audio file is longer than 60 minutes, the service splits it into segments and processes them sequentially, merging the results into a single coherent summary.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: The behavior explicitly chains: (a) audio split logic, (b) STT call per segment (multiple real ML calls — speaker diarization is non-deterministic across segment boundaries), (c) LLM merge call that must produce a coherent unified output. These are multiple real agentic steps in sequence. MOCK-HIDE: Stubbing the STT per segment hides whether speaker labels remain consistent across split boundaries (a real diarization model may re-label 'Speaker 1' differently in each chunk). Stubbing the LLM merge hides whether it actually produces coherent output when stitching potentially discontinuous segment summaries. LLM-DEP: 'Single coherent summary' is a quality judgment on the merge step — only a real LLM call can fail this. REJECTION-GATE: The behavior names both sequential processing of segments AND a coherent merged result; neither the sequential orchestration nor the merge quality can be validated by stubs without hiding real failures.","test_description":"Submit a real audio recording exceeding 60 minutes to the full service. Assert that: (1) the service produces multiple intermediate segment transcripts rather than one monolithic call, (2) speaker labels are consistent or reconciled across segment boundaries, (3) the final merged summary is a single coherent document with no duplicate action items or decisions from the segment boundary, and (4) the 'decisions' and 'action_items' fields represent the whole meeting, not just one segment.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.17,"Workflow":0.7}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full pipeline — upload audio, transcribe, summarize, deliver structured output — completes without manual intervention for a real meeting recording.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: The behavior explicitly names four sequential pipeline stages, each crossing a real boundary: (1) upload (real network/storage), (2) transcribe (real STT AI/ML API), (3) summarize (real LLM), (4) deliver structured output (real egress). No stage can be stubbed without hiding failures at that boundary. REAL-INFRA: Real HTTP, real file storage, and real external APIs are all required — in-process fakes collapse the boundary conditions where real failures occur (timeouts, auth errors, format mismatches). LLM-DEP: Both STT and LLM steps are real AI/ML calls; any stub replaces non-deterministic model behavior with a constant. REJECTION-GATE: 'Real meeting recording' and 'without manual intervention' are explicit disqualifiers for any lower level — the behavior is definitionally an end-to-end smoke test of the full agentic pipeline.","test_description":"Using a real meeting audio file (15–30 minutes, multiple speakers, with known decisions and task assignments), run the full service pipeline end-to-end: upload the file, trigger transcription, trigger summarization, and retrieve the structured output. Assert that the pipeline completes autonomously, the output is valid JSON matching the schema, contains non-empty 'decisions' and 'action_items' arrays, and that at least one attendee from the known recording is named. Measure and assert total wall-clock time is within an acceptable SLA.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.01,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.85}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9554,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9554},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4f25edd2-cd56-49c8-ba5b-0f6c36e01bb8","uuid":"129f5565-492d-4a9b-bd9b-3378f7d502fc"}
